      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Readers of your article ''If You're Thinking of Living in Tuxedo Park, N.Y.'' [June 18] might be interested in an important bit of American scientific history associated with the place.</p>
        <p>One house in Tuxedo park was the home of Alfred Lee Loomis, the last independent gentleman scientist, who established a well-known private research laboratory in the nearby Spencer Trask mansion.</p>
        <p>Loomis was a leader of World War II radar research and played a role in the first atomic bomb project. Many world-famous scientists attended conferences in Loomis's laboratory at Tuxedo Park and performed research there.</p>
        <p>Science was Loomis's hobby. By profession he was an investment banker, the financier who hired Wendell Willkie to be president of Commonwealth &amp; Southern Utilities.</p>
        <p>RICHARD H. TOURIN  Flushing, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
